                                                <td valign="top" class="mcnTextContent" style="padding-top: 0;padding-right: 18px;padding-bottom: 9px;padding-left: 18px;mso-line-height-rule: exactly;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;word-break: break-word;color: #1a1515;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 14px;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">
                                                
                                                    <link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Inter&display=swap" rel="stylesheet"><font color="#1a1515" face="inter, sans-serif"><span style="font-size:18px">The U.S. Open starts on Thursday, but golf has been in the news lately for a different reason: The LIV Golf Tour. The new golf circuit has made all sorts of headlines, albeit not exactly for the best reasons. We decided to get to the bottom of the controversy surrounding the new upstart league, their golfers, and the comparisons being made between it and The PGA Tour. To help explain, we asked Nick Schreiber, founder of Old Barnwell Golf Club, to take a swing at it.</span></font>
                                                </td>
                                            </tr>
