                        </table><table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="100%" class="mcnTextBlock" style="min-width: 100%;border-collapse: collapse;mso-table-lspace: 0pt;mso-table-rspace: 0pt;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;">
                            <tbody class="mcnTextBlockOuter">
                                <tr>
                                    <td valign="top" class="mcnTextBlockInner" style="padding-top: 9px;mso-line-height-rule: exactly;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;">
                                          <!--[if mso]>
                                        <table align="left" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%" style="width:100%;">
                                        <tr>
                                        <![endif]-->
                                        
                                        <!--[if mso]>
                                        <td valign="top" width="600" style="width:600px;">
                                        <![endif]-->
                                        <table align="left" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="max-width: 100%;min-width: 100%;border-collapse: collapse;mso-table-lspace: 0pt;mso-table-rspace: 0pt;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;" width="100%" class="mcnTextContentContainer">
                                            <tbody><tr>
                                                
                                                <td valign="top" class="mcnTextContent" style="padding-top: 0;padding-right: 18px;padding-bottom: 9px;padding-left: 18px;mso-line-height-rule: exactly;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;word-break: break-word;color: #1a1515;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 14px;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">
                                                
                                                    <link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Inter&display=swap" rel="stylesheet">
                        <style type="text/css">blockquote {
                            margin-left: 15px;
                            border-left-style: solid;
                            border-left-width: 1px;
                            border-left-color: #F25252;
                            padding-bottom: 10px;
                            padding: 5px;
                        }
                        </style>
                        <hr><font color="#1a1515" face="inter, sans-serif"><span style="font-size:18px"><strong>What is LIV Golf, and how is it different from the PGA Tour?</strong></span></font>
                        
                        <blockquote style="mso-line-height-rule: exactly;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;margin-left: 15px;border-left-style: solid;border-left-width: 1px;border-left-color: #F25252;padding-bottom: 10px;padding: 5px;"><font color="#1a1515" face="inter, sans-serif"><span style="font-size:18px"><em>LIV Golf is a new league financially backed by the Public Investment Fund of Saudi Arabia. The differences between the two leagues are quite significant. To begin, the PGA Tour hosts four-round tournaments with up to 175 competitors nearly every week of the year. LIV Golf, on the other hand, will showcase just 48 golfers over three rounds, with eight events this year, and likely 14 events next year. The biggest difference, however, is the money. LIV not only paid huge sums of money to draw professionals to defect from the PGA Tour and the European Tour (upwards of $150M for Dustin Johnson, and even more for Phil Mickelson), the tournament prize money it is offering is nearly quadruple that of the PGA Tour. For example, when Rory McIlroy beat out some of the world’s best golfers at the Canadian Open last weekend, he won about $1.5M. At the LIV event outside of London, Charles Schwartzl defeated a much less impressive field, but walked away with $4.75M.&nbsp;</em></span></font></blockquote>
                        <br>
                        <font color="#1a1515" face="inter, sans-serif"><span style="font-size:18px"><strong>Why is LIV Golf so controversial?</strong></span></font>
                        
                        <blockquote style="mso-line-height-rule: exactly;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;margin-left: 15px;border-left-style: solid;border-left-width: 1px;border-left-color: #F25252;padding-bottom: 10px;padding: 5px;"><em><font color="#1a1515" face="inter, sans-serif"><span style="font-size:18px">The fact that the Public Investment Fund of Saudi Arabia is financing the entire operation is the main hot button issue. With a nearly unlimited war chest of money with which to pay players, the government of Saudi Arabia is hoping to use LIV Golf to improve its international reputation via the sport. This is called “<a href="https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/golf/2022/06/10/sportswashing-explained-saudis-liv-golf/10003676002/" target="_blank" style="mso-line-height-rule: exactly;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #f25252;font-weight: normal;text-decoration: underline;">sportswashing</a>,” and LIV critics say that players such as Phil Mickelson and Dustin Johnson are willing participants in supporting a regime most recently in the news for <a href="https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-45812399" target="_blank" style="mso-line-height-rule: exactly;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #f25252;font-weight: normal;text-decoration: underline;">murdering</a> journalist Jamal Khashoggi and holding a mass <a href="https://www.hrw.org/news/2022/03/15/saudi-arabia-mass-execution-81-men" target="_blank" style="mso-line-height-rule: exactly;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #f25252;font-weight: normal;text-decoration: underline;">execution event</a> in which 81 people were beheaded. Last week, a coalition of families and survivors of the attacks on 9/11 (in which 15 of the 19 hijackers were Saudi nationals), wrote a letter pleading with pros like Mickelson to reconsider their defection to the new tour.&nbsp;</span></font></em></blockquote>
                        <br>
                        <font color="#1a1515" face="inter, sans-serif"><span style="font-size:18px"><strong>Will LIV Golf replace the PGA Tour?&nbsp;</strong></span></font>
                        
                        <blockquote style="mso-line-height-rule: exactly;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;margin-left: 15px;border-left-style: solid;border-left-width: 1px;border-left-color: #F25252;padding-bottom: 10px;padding: 5px;"><font color="#1a1515" face="inter, sans-serif"><span style="font-size:18px"><em></em><em>At this point, it remains unclear. The PGA Tour has suspended (or intends to suspend) all PGA Tour pros who tee it up in a LIV event, kickstarting a legal battle that could hinder both sides. &nbsp;It is increasingly clear, however, that the PGA Tour needs to do more to reward the biggest names in golf, who are comparatively underpaid. Other concerns from Tour players include too many tournaments each year and not enough control over their digital media rights. These are not easy issues to fix overnight, and the LIV Tour continues to add starpower to its lineup (just a few days ago, Bryson DeChambeau and Patrick Reed announced their intention to play at next week’s LIV event in Portland, Oregon). The appeal of fewer tournaments and absurd amounts of money make the LIV tour very appealing for mid-level Tour pros, and up and coming amateurs who face a long road to succes via the traditional path on the PGA Tour. With so much money behind it, LIV Golf certainly has the resources to torpedo the old way of professional golf. But generational talents like Tiger Woods, Rory McIlroy, and Justin Thomas have stated in no uncertain terms: if you want to play against the best, if you want to build a legacy of championship play, the only place to do so is the PGA Tour. Whether or not that is the case in 12 or 24 months remains to be seen. &nbsp;</em></span></font></blockquote>
                        
                                                </td>
                                            </tr>
